1
00:00:43,301 --> 00:00:45,633
Hey, buddy.

2
00:00:45,633 --> 00:00:47,633
You don't waste time, do you?

3
00:00:47,633 --> 00:00:49,367
I try not to.

4
00:00:49,367 --> 00:00:50,667
Well, you need help?

5
00:00:50,667 --> 00:00:51,767
Sure.

6
00:00:55,501 --> 00:00:57,234
Would you like to tell us...

7
00:00:57,234 --> 00:00:59,633
what the hell that was all about?

8
00:00:59,633 --> 00:01:01,000
I don't like good-byes.

9
00:01:01,000 --> 00:01:04,367
Kind of the point of
a goodbye party, John.

10
00:01:04,367 --> 00:01:06,667
Went to a certain amount
of trouble, you know?

11
00:01:06,667 --> 00:01:08,900
Could've at least stayed
a few minutes, huh?

12
00:01:08,900 --> 00:01:12,800
Eaten some of the food
we so feverishly prepared?

13
00:01:12,800 --> 00:01:14,434
I apologize, Harry.

14
00:01:14,434 --> 00:01:16,034
But why are you moving so quickly?

15
00:01:16,034 --> 00:01:17,800
You only resigned a couple of days ago.

16
00:01:17,800 --> 00:01:20,234
You got the history chair at Stanford.

17
00:01:20,234 --> 00:01:21,367
I wish.

18
00:01:21,367 --> 00:01:23,434
Well, taquitos, chicken wings,

19
00:01:23,434 --> 00:01:25,700
Roastie-toasties and beer.

20
00:01:25,700 --> 00:01:27,267
If we'd had more time,

21
00:01:27,267 --> 00:01:29,301
We'd have done something
a little more grandiose.

22
00:01:29,301 --> 00:01:31,067
Candlelight dinner at Mcdonald's.

23
00:01:31,067 --> 00:01:32,667
Strippers.

24
00:01:32,667 --> 00:01:34,468
Taquitos are fine.

25
00:01:34,468 --> 00:01:36,434
A'right.

26
00:01:36,434 --> 00:01:38,234
Art's gonna be along, too.

27
00:01:38,234 --> 00:01:40,000
He's, uh, talking to a student. Pfft.

28
00:01:40,000 --> 00:01:41,934
Is George taking over for you?

29
00:01:41,934 --> 00:01:44,600
George or Trimbell - Has
the Dean made up his mind?

30
00:01:44,600 --> 00:01:45,700
He hasn't called.

31
00:01:45,700 --> 00:01:46,767
My god!

32
00:01:46,767 --> 00:01:48,201
Wh-What is this?

33
00:01:48,201 --> 00:01:49,501
It looks like a Van Gogh,

34
00:01:49,501 --> 00:01:50,733
But I've never seen it before.

35
00:01:50,733 --> 00:01:52,401
Is that an original, John?

36
00:01:52,401 --> 00:01:54,733
No, it's just a gift someone gave me.

37
00:01:54,733 --> 00:01:57,067
Still, it's a superb copy.

38
00:01:57,067 --> 00:01:58,667
Contemporaneous, I think,

39
00:01:58,667 --> 00:02:00,600
May I take a closer look?

40
00:02:00,600 --> 00:02:01,733
Please, yeah.

41
00:02:03,934 --> 00:02:06,468
Yeah, it's the same
stretcher as Van Gogh used.

42
00:02:06,468 --> 00:02:09,134
Yeah, there's writing
on the back in french.

43
00:02:09,134 --> 00:02:11,568
Oh, "To my friend Jacque Borne."

44
00:02:11,568 --> 00:02:12,834
Wonder who that was?

45
00:02:12,834 --> 00:02:14,334
Someone he knew, I guess.

46
00:02:14,334 --> 00:02:16,034
Brilliant deduction, sherlock.

47
00:02:16,034 --> 00:02:18,934
Surely you'll have this
looked at, appraised?

48
00:02:18,934 --> 00:02:20,967
Well, maybe sometime,

49
00:02:20,967 --> 00:02:24,201
But I wouldn't really want money for it.

50
00:02:25,700 --> 00:02:27,934
That does it.

51
00:02:27,934 --> 00:02:29,800
Put that stuff in the kitchen.

52
00:02:29,800 --> 00:02:33,301
No, I'm gonna put it
in the bathroom, John.

53
00:02:33,301 --> 00:02:35,568
Gas is off, electricity's on.

54
00:02:37,267 --> 00:02:38,834
Get comfortable while you can.

55
00:02:38,834 --> 00:02:40,967
The furniture's going this afternoon.

56
00:02:40,967 --> 00:02:43,834
It's been years since I sat on a floor.

57
00:02:43,834 --> 00:02:45,900
Heh. I can't remember her name.

58
00:02:45,900 --> 00:02:47,700
Eh, it's good for the back.

59
00:02:47,700 --> 00:02:49,034
Can we do yoga exercises?

60
00:02:49,034 --> 00:02:51,167
Tantric yoga, we can.

61
00:02:51,167 --> 00:02:52,534
( Chuckles )

62
00:02:52,534 --> 00:02:55,134
So you're leaving good old "We teach you"?

63
00:02:55,134 --> 00:02:58,201
Rather suddenly, you must admit.

64
00:02:58,201 --> 00:02:59,900
Truth time, John.

65
00:02:59,900 --> 00:03:01,534
Is there a problem?

66
00:03:01,534 --> 00:03:02,934
No.

67
00:03:02,934 --> 00:03:05,401
Oh, come on, you know we wanna help.

68
00:03:05,401 --> 00:03:07,301
That's appreciated,
but really--

69
00:03:07,301 --> 00:03:08,568
There's no problem.

70
00:03:08,568 --> 00:03:11,334
Well, now I am curious.

71
00:03:11,334 --> 00:03:12,534
Where are you going?

72
00:03:12,534 --> 00:03:13,534
Givin' up tenure...

73
00:03:13,534 --> 00:03:15,534
a decade of professorship,

74
00:03:15,534 --> 00:03:17,967
In line to chair the department,

75
00:03:17,967 --> 00:03:20,800
And you don't know where you're going?

76
00:03:20,800 --> 00:03:22,301
Call it cabin fever.

77
00:03:22,301 --> 00:03:24,800
After a while, I get itchy feet.

78
00:03:24,800 --> 00:03:26,134
I've done this before.

79
00:03:26,134 --> 00:03:29,201
No, no, no, you're too young
to have done this before.

80
00:03:29,201 --> 00:03:31,501
And he hasn't aged a day in ten years.

81
00:03:31,501 --> 00:03:33,067
Every woman on the faculty

82
00:03:33,067 --> 00:03:35,633
Would give anything to have that secret.

83
00:03:35,633 --> 00:03:37,234
Is that what they're after, Edith?

84
00:03:37,234 --> 00:03:38,900
Oh, stop, Harry.

85
00:03:38,900 --> 00:03:41,733
( Giggles )

86
00:03:41,733 --> 00:03:43,301
Wow, can you pull this?

87
00:03:45,034 --> 00:03:46,134
What the hell?

88
00:03:46,134 --> 00:03:47,600
What do you hunt?

89
00:03:47,600 --> 00:03:48,934
Deer, mostly.

90
00:03:48,934 --> 00:03:50,101
Around big bear.

91
00:03:50,101 --> 00:03:51,501
With a bow and arrow?

92
00:03:51,501 --> 00:03:53,267
Most people can't bag a deer

93
00:03:53,267 --> 00:03:55,267
With a rifle and a telescopic sight.

94
00:03:55,267 --> 00:03:57,034
Though, good eatin'.

95
00:03:57,034 --> 00:03:58,468
The best wild game.

96
00:03:58,468 --> 00:04:00,234
Lives naturally, eats naturally.

97
00:04:00,234 --> 00:04:01,600
Well, it's beautiful.

98
00:04:03,401 --> 00:04:04,700
( Motor hums )

99
00:04:04,700 --> 00:04:06,434
Art.

100
00:04:08,134 --> 00:04:09,800
Ah.

101
00:04:09,800 --> 00:04:13,067
So, can I get an "a" for awesome?

102
00:04:13,067 --> 00:04:14,134
Oh, my gosh.

103
00:04:14,134 --> 00:04:15,134
( Chuckles )

104
00:04:15,134 --> 00:04:16,600
That was fun.

105
00:04:16,600 --> 00:04:18,367
Hey, John.

106
00:04:18,367 --> 00:04:20,800
You know Linda. You
had her last semester.

107
00:04:20,800 --> 00:04:22,201
Hi. Hey.

108
00:04:22,201 --> 00:04:24,334
She's one of my victims
now. I'm taking her home.

109
00:04:24,334 --> 00:04:26,000
She wanted to come by
and say hello goodbye.

110
00:04:26,000 --> 00:04:27,568
Is Art as tough as I hear?

111
00:04:27,568 --> 00:04:28,900
Oh, archaeology's tough.

112
00:04:28,900 --> 00:04:31,234
Dr. Jenkins is a fine teacher.

113
00:04:31,234 --> 00:04:32,900
Oh, that's very politic.

114
00:04:32,900 --> 00:04:34,501
It's very true. Uh-huh.

115
00:04:34,501 --> 00:04:37,000
Something for you to
read on the road, pal.

116
00:04:37,000 --> 00:04:39,900
<i>"Shadows of the cave:
parallels to early man."</i>

117
00:04:39,900 --> 00:04:41,733
Author: M. Jenkins.

118
00:04:41,733 --> 00:04:42,733
Publish or perish.

119
00:04:42,733 --> 00:04:43,733
I'd rather read

120
00:04:43,733 --> 00:04:44,800
Than write another one.

121
00:04:44,800 --> 00:04:46,733
Thank you.

122
00:04:46,733 --> 00:04:48,034
Hi.

123
00:04:48,034 --> 00:04:50,700
Oh, everybody, this is Linda.

124
00:04:50,700 --> 00:04:52,534
Linda, this is everybody.

125
00:04:52,534 --> 00:04:54,101
Linda. Hi.

126
00:04:54,101 --> 00:04:56,401
So.

127
00:04:56,401 --> 00:04:58,900
Where you going, John,
like we give a damn?

128
00:04:58,900 --> 00:05:00,101
We've already covered that.

129
00:05:00,101 --> 00:05:02,600
John's got itchy feet.

130
00:05:02,600 --> 00:05:04,900
There are over-the-counter
remedies for that, John.

131
00:05:04,900 --> 00:05:06,334
( Laughs )

132
00:05:07,834 --> 00:05:09,167
So there is a problem.

133
00:05:09,167 --> 00:05:11,000
No.

134
00:05:11,000 --> 00:05:13,301
I just like to move on now and then.

135
00:05:13,301 --> 00:05:14,667
It's a personal thing.

136
00:05:16,134 --> 00:05:18,134
Well, not to pry.

137
00:05:25,700 --> 00:05:28,600
I'm sorry I don't
have more to offer you.

138
00:05:28,600 --> 00:05:31,134
Got conversation, some
seats for your behinds,

139
00:05:31,134 --> 00:05:32,201
And, uh...

140
00:05:35,967 --> 00:05:38,468
Is he ducking out on us again?

141
00:05:39,900 --> 00:05:41,600
...I do have this.

142
00:05:41,600 --> 00:05:46,267
Oh ho ho! Johnny Walker Green!

143
00:05:46,267 --> 00:05:49,034
( Laughs ) didn't even
know they made it in green.

144
00:05:49,034 --> 00:05:50,534
What do they pay you?

145
00:05:50,534 --> 00:05:52,501
Nothing is too good for my friends.

146
00:05:52,501 --> 00:05:55,468
But I'm sorry-- We are
down to plastic cups now.

147
00:05:55,468 --> 00:05:57,468
That's a sacrilege I'll tolerate.

148
00:05:57,468 --> 00:05:59,167
I will do the honors.

149
00:05:59,167 --> 00:06:00,800
Oh, come to papa.

150
00:06:02,401 --> 00:06:03,900
Ooh! Here, cups, cups.

151
00:06:03,900 --> 00:06:04,967
There we go.

152
00:06:04,967 --> 00:06:06,000
Step on in here.

153
00:06:06,000 --> 00:06:07,201
There ya go...

154
00:06:07,201 --> 00:06:09,667
one for the birthday
boy-- Excuse me. Art?

155
00:06:09,667 --> 00:06:10,834
No, not for me.

156
00:06:10,834 --> 00:06:12,234
Oh, no, I don't drink.

157
00:06:12,234 --> 00:06:14,134
( Laughs ) we're not
gonna card you, darling.

158
00:06:14,134 --> 00:06:16,301
All right, here, join
the circle at least.

159
00:06:16,301 --> 00:06:21,000
Well, to long life and good fortune

160
00:06:21,000 --> 00:06:22,600
To our esteemed friend

161
00:06:22,600 --> 00:06:24,334
And colleague, John Oldman.

162
00:06:24,334 --> 00:06:26,434
May he find undeserved bliss

163
00:06:26,434 --> 00:06:27,667
Wherever he goes.

164
00:06:27,667 --> 00:06:28,700
Here, here.

165
00:06:28,700 --> 00:06:30,367
<i>Skael. Na zdorovye.</i>

166
00:06:30,367 --> 00:06:32,468
One off the top, John.

167
00:06:37,568 --> 00:06:39,301
Mm! Oh, that's good.

168
00:06:39,301 --> 00:06:40,501
Excuse me.

169
00:06:42,733 --> 00:06:46,101
John, we're all sorry to see you go.

170
00:06:46,101 --> 00:06:47,201
Truly.

171
00:06:49,700 --> 00:06:51,834
Okay. Now we're done with that,

172
00:06:51,834 --> 00:06:53,834
What do we do for the
rest of the afternoon?

173
00:06:53,834 --> 00:06:55,568
Anyone got a good topic?

174
00:06:55,568 --> 00:06:57,434
Like this, maybe? Heh.

175
00:06:57,434 --> 00:06:58,501
What is that?

176
00:06:58,501 --> 00:07:01,234
It's a burin of a parrot beak.

177
00:07:01,234 --> 00:07:02,733
Inclined chisel point...

178
00:07:02,733 --> 00:07:04,900
probably early magdalenian.

179
00:07:04,900 --> 00:07:07,167
May I see that? Sure.

180
00:07:13,267 --> 00:07:15,000
Yes indeed, that's what it is.

181
00:07:16,234 --> 00:07:17,468
What's a burin?

182
00:07:17,468 --> 00:07:19,134
A burin is a flint tool

183
00:07:19,134 --> 00:07:21,733
For grooving wood and
bone, antlers especially,

184
00:07:21,733 --> 00:07:24,267
To make spear and harpoon points.

185
00:07:24,267 --> 00:07:26,267
Magdalenians weren't
noted for flint work,

186
00:07:26,267 --> 00:07:28,034
So this is a very nice specimen.

187
00:07:28,034 --> 00:07:30,534
Okay, what's a magdalenian?

188
00:07:30,534 --> 00:07:32,000
A later Cro-magnon,

189
00:07:32,000 --> 00:07:33,334
Without gettin' technical.

190
00:07:33,334 --> 00:07:36,468
It's the final culture
of the upper paleolithic.

191
00:07:36,468 --> 00:07:38,401
If stones could speak, eh, Art?

192
00:07:38,401 --> 00:07:40,067
So where'd you get that, John?

193
00:07:40,067 --> 00:07:42,633
Believe it or not, from
a thrift shop-- A quarter.

194
00:07:42,633 --> 00:07:44,234
You lucky dog!

195
00:07:44,234 --> 00:07:46,501
I gotta go digging
for this kind of stuff.

196
00:07:46,501 --> 00:07:47,733
Can I, uh...?

197
00:07:47,733 --> 00:07:48,767
Yeah.

198
00:07:52,167 --> 00:07:53,301
Huh.

199
00:07:58,334 --> 00:08:00,067
Maybe...

200
00:08:00,067 --> 00:08:01,667
I'm glad you did this.

201
00:08:01,667 --> 00:08:04,468
Did what? You mean come over?

202
00:08:04,468 --> 00:08:06,234
Maybe?

203
00:08:06,234 --> 00:08:07,501
Definitely.

204
00:08:07,501 --> 00:08:08,800
Gee, thanks.

205
00:08:08,800 --> 00:08:10,201
Well, so are we.

206
00:08:10,201 --> 00:08:11,667
So are we.

207
00:08:11,667 --> 00:08:13,800
We couldn't let you just run off.

208
00:08:13,800 --> 00:08:15,000
Thanks.

209
00:08:17,034 --> 00:08:18,834
John, what is up, huh?

210
00:08:18,834 --> 00:08:20,334
<i>Are you on america's most wanted?</i>

211
00:08:20,334 --> 00:08:21,534
We won't turn you in.

212
00:08:21,534 --> 00:08:22,900
Yeah, come on, out with it.

213
00:08:22,900 --> 00:08:23,900
You're among friends.

214
00:08:23,900 --> 00:08:25,167
Snoopy friends.

215
00:08:25,167 --> 00:08:26,234
Forget it.

216
00:08:26,234 --> 00:08:27,900
You are creating the mystery here.

217
00:08:27,900 --> 00:08:30,201
Obviously, you have something
you'd like to say. Say it!

218
00:08:31,834 --> 00:08:33,468
Well, maybe I...

219
00:08:34,600 --> 00:08:35,834
ten, nine, eight, seven...

220
00:08:35,834 --> 00:08:36,900
Harry, stop.

221
00:08:38,401 --> 00:08:41,301
There is something I'm
tempted to tell you, I think.

222
00:08:41,301 --> 00:08:44,900
I've never done this before,
and I wonder how it'll pan out.

223
00:08:44,900 --> 00:08:46,733
( Harry chuckles )

224
00:08:48,067 --> 00:08:50,367
I wonder if I could ask
you a silly question.

225
00:08:50,367 --> 00:08:51,401
John, we're teachers.

226
00:08:51,401 --> 00:08:53,334
We answer silly questions all the time.

227
00:08:53,334 --> 00:08:54,468
Hey!

228
00:08:54,468 --> 00:08:58,134
What if a man from the upper paleolithic

229
00:08:58,134 --> 00:09:00,234
Survived until the present day?

230
00:09:00,234 --> 00:09:01,767
What do you mean, survived?

231
00:09:01,767 --> 00:09:03,134
Never died?

232
00:09:03,134 --> 00:09:05,201
Yes. What would he be like?

233
00:09:05,201 --> 00:09:06,767
Well, I know some guys.

234
00:09:06,767 --> 00:09:08,733
You ever been to the ozarks?

235
00:09:08,733 --> 00:09:10,401
It's an interesting idea.

236
00:09:10,401 --> 00:09:12,900
What, are you working on
a science fiction story?

237
00:09:12,900 --> 00:09:15,167
Say I am. What would he be like?

238
00:09:15,167 --> 00:09:16,167
Pretty tired.

239
00:09:16,167 --> 00:09:17,767
( Laughter )

240
00:09:17,767 --> 00:09:20,167
Well, seriously,

241
00:09:20,167 --> 00:09:22,167
As Art's book title suggests,

242
00:09:22,167 --> 00:09:24,501
He might be like any of us.

243
00:09:24,501 --> 00:09:25,834
Dan. A caveman?

244
00:09:25,834 --> 00:09:27,468
Well, there's no anatomical difference

245
00:09:27,468 --> 00:09:29,468
Between, say, a Cro-magnon and us.

246
00:09:29,468 --> 00:09:31,967
Except that as a rule,
we've grown taller.

247
00:09:31,967 --> 00:09:34,267
What's the selective
advantage of height?

248
00:09:34,267 --> 00:09:37,000
Better to see predators
in tall grass, my dear.

249
00:09:37,000 --> 00:09:39,334
Actually, tall and skinny

250
00:09:39,334 --> 00:09:42,201
Radiates heat more
effectively in warmer climates.

251
00:09:42,201 --> 00:09:43,534
And as for neanderthals,

252
00:09:43,534 --> 00:09:45,234
I mean, we've all seen apish people.

253
00:09:45,234 --> 00:09:46,468
That strain's still with us.

254
00:09:46,468 --> 00:09:48,600
But he'd be a caveman.

255
00:09:48,600 --> 00:09:49,667
No, he wouldn't.

256
00:09:49,667 --> 00:09:50,700
John's hypothetical man

257
00:09:50,700 --> 00:09:52,468
Would have lived
through 140 centuries...

258
00:09:52,468 --> 00:09:53,900
yeah, roughly.

259
00:09:53,900 --> 00:09:56,301
...and changed with every one of them.

260
00:09:56,301 --> 00:09:58,667
I mean, assuming normal intelligence.

261
00:09:58,667 --> 00:10:01,134
Well, we think men of
the upper paleolithic

262
00:10:01,134 --> 00:10:02,967
Were as intelligent as we are.

263
00:10:02,967 --> 00:10:04,834
They just didn't know as much.

264
00:10:04,834 --> 00:10:07,800
John's man would have
learned as the race learned.

265
00:10:07,800 --> 00:10:10,501
In fact, if he had an inquiring mind,

266
00:10:10,501 --> 00:10:14,101
His knowledge might be astonishing.

267
00:10:14,101 --> 00:10:16,667
If you do write that,
let me have a look at it.

268
00:10:16,667 --> 00:10:18,633
I'm sure you'll make some
anthropological boners.

269
00:10:18,633 --> 00:10:19,767
It's a deal.

270
00:10:19,767 --> 00:10:21,568
What would keep him alive?

271
00:10:21,568 --> 00:10:23,468
What does the biologist say?

272
00:10:23,468 --> 00:10:25,167
Cigarettes.

